AB  - Conventional statistics were used to study the variability of the soils in Hell Hook marsh along the Chesapeake Bay in Dorchester County, Maryland. Analysis of variance and least significant difference test suggested that the differentiating characteristics and the accessory physical and chemical properties were significantly different among three pedons located 20 m apart. The spatial distribution of the mean coefficient of variation demonstrated that the spatial variability of organic carbon and total sulfur within a pedon is random rather than systematic. The magnitude of variability among and within pedons substantiates the importance of establishing a feasible sampling protocol. However, because of the great variability of tidal marsh soils, there is often the need to balance the desire for high confidence level and accuracy with the need for a reasonable sampling protocol. This was accomplished by accepting an 80% confidence level and 20% accuracy rather than more rigorous estimates and was achieved by making a single observation to estimate the thickness of the organic horizon and by collecting three samples, on average, within 1 to 2 m to estimate total sulfur and organic carbon.
