T2  - Ecology
M3  - Journal Article
AB  - Biodiversity plays important roles in nature's contributions to people (i.e. ecosystem services), but the critical details of how biodiversity contributes are challenging to determine. Efforts to identify the components of an ecosystem that provide services have improved our understanding of which species, functional groups, population, or habitats directly provide services. However, species do not exist in isolation - and considerably less is known about how species indirectly influence ecosystem services, through interacting with those species directly providing services. This uncertainty is even greater when considering that species interact in complex networks. As such, detailed analysis of species interdependencies are rarely included in ecosystem services assessments or conservation decisions. To date, most studies on food webs and on ecosystem services have developed largely in parallel for many services, but these fields and data are ripe for empirical integration. To further this integration, we compile datasets that link three existing ecological networks to seven ecosystem functions and services: wave attenuation, shoreline stabilization, carbon sequestration, water filtration, fisheries, birdwatching, and waterfowl hunting. We leveraged high-resolution ecological interaction network datasets from three coastal salt marsh ecosystems including detailed species information (e.g. consumer strategy, body size, biomass) on several hundred species from Carpinteria Salt Marsh in California, USA, and for Estero de Punta Banda and Bahia Falsa in Baja, Mexico. Through an extensive literature synthesis and use of citizen science data, we identified which species in the Hechinger et al. (2011) dataset provide each ecosystem services directly. We augmented the Hechinger et al. (2011) dataset published in Ecology, particularly the link (or edge) list to include species - service links - indicating a species providing a service - where species are listed as "Resources" and services are listed as "Consumers." Connecting this data to the previously published ecological networks with species interactions (i.e., trophic, parasitism) forms a topological network with species and service nodes. We also provide a protocol for assigning services to ecological networks that can be used in other ecosystems. This dataset provides a step towards advancing knowledge of important supporting species for ecosystem services and developing new ecological network methods for ecosystem services. There are no copyright restrictions; please cite this data paper when the data are used in publications.
